...l- N-E.

9
00:02:32,656 --> 00:02:34,248
Quarantine.

10
00:02:34,458 --> 00:02:36,016
You know the cholera?

11
00:02:36,193 --> 00:02:37,717
Yes, Mother.

12
00:02:37,895 --> 00:02:40,830
You've seen the signs on
the houses where the coloreds live?

13
00:02:40,998 --> 00:02:42,659
Yes, Mother.

14
00:02:42,833 --> 00:02:44,095
You know the typhus?

15
00:02:44,268 --> 00:02:46,327
I do, Mother.

16
00:02:49,239 --> 00:02:51,264
You know what they
can do to you?

17
00:02:52,109 --> 00:02:53,667
Yes, Mother.

18
00:02:57,614 --> 00:02:59,980
You are not safe.

19
00:03:06,990 --> 00:03:10,585
You may be directing this movie,
but what you're asking, we can't do.

20
00:03:11,929 --> 00:03:13,624
Don't tell me it can't be done.

21
00:03:13,797 --> 00:03:17,563
The gyro forces are too much.
You send these planes into barrel rolls...

22
00:03:17,734 --> 00:03:21,226
...they won't make it.
- It's the climax of the picture. Make it work.

23
00:03:21,405 --> 00:03:23,896
Decrease the vertical trajectory
if you have to.

24
00:03:24,074 --> 00:03:26,565
A Le Rhône rotary
won't stall at 60 degrees.

25
00:03:26,743 --> 00:03:30,304
We're still short two cameras.
We need to cut that sequence down...

26
00:03:30,480 --> 00:03:33,881
We're not cutting. I'll get those cameras.
Set up for rehearsals.

27
00:03:34,051 --> 00:03:36,849
I'm Noah Dietrich.
Your office said I'd find you here.

28
00:03:37,020 --> 00:03:39,113
Dietrich.
You're a man on the come.

29
00:03:39,289 --> 00:03:43,123
I read your résumé, talked to your references.
Know what I'm looking for?

30
00:03:43,293 --> 00:03:46,319
You're looking for a second-in-command
at Hughes Tools.

31
00:03:46,496 --> 00:03:49,260
Someone to oversee
the financial aspects of the business.

32
00:03:49,433 --> 00:03:52,197
I'm looking for somebody to run it
and do a good job.

33
00:03:52,369 --> 00:03:54,633
There's only one thing
you've gotta know.

34
00:03:54,805 --> 00:03:57,638
My folks, they're gone now.
So it's my money.

35
00:03:57,808 --> 00:04:01,539
What I do with that money may seem crazy
to those sons of bitches in Houston.

36
00:04:01,712 --> 00:04:05,273
I'm sure it does, but it all makes
good sense to me. You got that?

37
00:04:05,449 --> 00:04:07,246
- Got it.
- Good.

38
00:04:07,417 --> 00:04:10,545
Now, you made, what,
$5200 a year at your last job?

39
00:04:10,721 --> 00:04:14,589
- I'll pay you $ 10,000.
- I guess I'll be working twice as hard.

40
00:04:14,758 --> 00:04:18,319
You'll be working four times as hard.
I just got you at half price.

41
00:04:18,495 --> 00:04:19,985
- Welcome aboard.
- Thank you.

42
00:04:20,163 --> 00:04:22,324
You're my voice now.
Make them understand that.

43
00:04:22,499 --> 00:04:26,663
Some of those folks still call me Junior.
You tell them it's "Mr. Hughes" now.

44
00:04:26,837 --> 00:04:28,930
You bet.
So when do we go to Houston?

45
00:04:29,106 --> 00:04:32,371
We don't. Cholera epidemic in 1913.
Two thousand dead.

46
00:04:32,542 --> 00:04:34,601
Whole place is nothing but
pestilential swamp.

47
00:04:34,778 --> 00:04:38,874
Typhus, malaria, cholera, yellow fever.
You name it, they got it.

48
00:04:39,049 --> 00:04:40,516
You see that, Mr. Dietrich?

49
00:04:41,518 --> 00:04:45,579
You are looking at the largest
private air force in the entire world.

50
00:04:45,756 --> 00:04:47,781
What do you think of that, now?

51
00:04:49,192 --> 00:04:50,750
It's your money.

52
00:04:50,928 --> 00:04:53,328
Start them up!

53
00:06:19,282 --> 00:06:23,116
<i>I saw the rough cut of the new
Tod Browning movie, London After Midnight.</i>

54
00:06:23,286 --> 00:06:25,083
Lon Chaney is incredible.

55
00:06:25,255 --> 00:06:27,587
It's his best performance
in a long time.

56
00:06:27,758 --> 00:06:30,090
It's gonna be a big hit.
The cards are great.

57
00:06:30,260 --> 00:06:31,693
It's supposed to be...

58
00:06:31,862 --> 00:06:34,296
Hello, Mr. Mayer.

59
00:06:34,464 --> 00:06:37,456
I don't know if you remember me.
My name's Howard Hughes.

60
00:06:37,634 --> 00:06:40,000
I was wondering
if I could have a moment.

61
00:06:40,170 --> 00:06:43,230
- Oh, Howard Hughes. The airplane picture?
- Exactly.

62
00:06:43,407 --> 00:06:45,739
<i>- I remember.
- Hell's Angels. You heard of it.</i>

63
00:06:45,909 --> 00:06:47,137
- Good.
- Yes.

64
00:06:47,310 --> 00:06:50,108
I was wondering if I could
have a moment of your time.

65
00:06:50,280 --> 00:06:51,577
I need a few cameras.

66
00:06:52,416 --> 00:06:55,408
- Yeah?
- Yeah, two, to be exact.

67
00:06:56,319 --> 00:07:00,346
I bought every camera I could find.
We're shooting our big dogfight sequence.

68
00:07:00,524 --> 00:07:03,960
I need two more. Desperately.
You think MGM could help me out?

69
00:07:04,261 --> 00:07:05,489
With what?

70
00:07:05,662 --> 00:07:08,460
- Cameras.
- Oh, with the actual cam...

71
00:07:08,632 --> 00:07:11,829
We're not usually in the practice
of helping out competition.

72
00:07:12,102 --> 00:07:15,128
- No. No.
- So how many cameras do you have now?

73
00:07:15,305 --> 00:07:16,670
Twenty-four.

74
00:07:19,242 --> 00:07:21,836
You...?
Wait a minute.

75
00:07:24,114 --> 00:07:25,979
- You have 24 cameras?
- That's right.

76
00:07:26,149 --> 00:07:28,743
- And you need...? You need two more?
- Yeah.

77
00:07:28,919 --> 00:07:32,514
- You don't think you got it with 24?
- No. No, sir.

78
00:07:32,689 --> 00:07:35,317
You know, I think...
I think we've got them all...

79
00:07:35,492 --> 00:07:37,926
Don't we have them...?
They're all used, right?

80
00:07:38,095 --> 00:07:40,359
- All 26 of them.
- I only need two, sir.

81
00:07:40,530 --> 00:07:42,395
- Jesus Christ, sonny.
- Howard.

82
00:07:42,566 --> 00:07:45,228
Howard. Let me give you
a little advice, huh?

83
00:07:45,402 --> 00:07:47,495
- Take your oil money...
- Drill bits.

84
00:07:47,671 --> 00:07:50,765
All right, take your drill-bit money
and put it in the bank.

85
00:07:50,941 --> 00:07:53,603
If you continue making
the movie the way you are...

86
00:07:53,777 --> 00:07:56,041
...there isn't gonna be a distributor...

87
00:07:56,213 --> 00:07:59,182
...you won't find anybody
who wants to see the movie...

88
00:07:59,349 --> 00:08:02,011
...and you're not gonna have
any more oil money.

89
00:08:02,185 --> 00:08:05,211
So welcome to Hollywood.

90
00:08:05,388 --> 00:08:08,789
Yeah. Well, I'll be sure
to remember that, Mr. Mayer.

91
00:08:08,959 --> 00:08:10,756
- Good luck.
- All right.

92
00:08:10,927 --> 00:08:14,124
He needs 26 to make it work?
He's out of his mind.

93
00:08:21,371 --> 00:08:24,204
I looked down at my pants.
It was a strange situation.

94
00:08:26,042 --> 00:08:28,772
Boss.
Scram, love boat, let's go.

95
00:08:30,013 --> 00:08:33,039
- Another soda. You know what I mean.
- Milk. In the bottle.

96
00:08:33,216 --> 00:08:36,185
- With the cap still on.
- Okay, what did His Highness say?

97
00:08:36,353 --> 00:08:39,550
Son of a bitch won't part with
a single goddamn camera.

98
00:08:39,723 --> 00:08:42,248
Why don't you try and
make do with what you have.

99
00:08:42,826 --> 00:08:45,590
What I have isn't enough, John,
not for how I see it.

100
00:08:45,762 --> 00:08:47,252
Look.

101
00:08:47,430 --> 00:08:51,366
My name depends on this picture.
If it doesn't work, I'm back to Houston...

102
00:08:51,535 --> 00:08:54,333
...making goddamn drill bits
for the rest of my life.

103
00:08:54,504 --> 00:08:56,665
Can't you do it
with the cameras you have?

104
00:08:56,840 --> 00:08:59,604
You ought to hear about
what's going on with DeMille.

105
00:08:59,776 --> 00:09:04,042
He's shooting his Bible picture.
He's gotta do a crucifixion in Fresno.

106
00:09:04,214 --> 00:09:05,442
Johnny.

107
00:09:05,615 --> 00:09:07,708
- A bunch of tractors...
- Johnny.

108
00:09:07,884 --> 00:09:10,045
- You're a press agent, are you not?
- Yeah.

109
00:09:10,220 --> 00:09:12,347
You're supposed to know
the ins and outs?

110
00:09:12,522 --> 00:09:13,750
- Absolutely.
- Do you?

111
00:09:13,924 --> 00:09:15,152
Yeah, absolutely.

112
00:09:15,325 --> 00:09:17,384
Then you leave the big ideas...

113
00:09:18,028 --> 00:09:20,121
...to me.
- Oh, yeah. Of course, boss.

114
00:09:20,297 --> 00:09:22,060
Cigar, cigarettes, Sen-Sen?

115
00:09:23,200 --> 00:09:25,361
I thought you were
at the Brown Derby...

116
00:09:25,535 --> 00:09:27,264
...with Trixie. No, Theresa.

117
00:09:27,437 --> 00:09:28,961
- Margaret.
- Margaret. Exactly.

118
00:09:29,139 --> 00:09:31,266
What happened to Margaret?
She lost her...

119
00:09:31,441 --> 00:09:32,965
Thank God that's settled.

120
00:09:33,143 --> 00:09:36,271
Oh, I'm sorry.
Thelma, this is Howard Hughes.

121
00:09:36,446 --> 00:09:40,439
Howard and I were discussing how he
wants me to pull a camera out of my ass.

122
00:09:41,284 --> 00:09:45,084
- Cigarette?
- Oh, no, thanks. I don't smoke.

123
00:09:47,924 --> 00:09:51,223
Boy, you are just hitting
on all six cylinders, aren't you?

124
00:09:51,394 --> 00:09:53,259
My God.

125
00:09:53,863 --> 00:09:56,058
Would you do me
a favor and just...?

126
00:09:56,233 --> 00:09:58,895
Would you just smile
for me one time? Just once?

127
00:10:02,172 --> 00:10:04,800
Yeah. Yeah. You see,
you got a short upper lip.

128
00:10:05,175 --> 00:10:06,972
Makes for a much nicer smile.

129
00:10:12,148 --> 00:10:15,743
See, I wonder what gives
a beautiful woman like you pleasure.

130
00:10:15,986 --> 00:10:19,581
I mean, say you're just standing
there, right? And I just touch you.

131
00:10:19,756 --> 00:10:21,747
Just... Just like this.

132
00:10:22,359 --> 00:10:23,724
With my fingertips.

133
00:10:23,893 --> 00:10:26,123
Do you...?
Do you like that?

134
00:10:27,230 --> 00:10:28,822
Do you?

135
00:10:33,837 --> 00:10:36,863
You see, I wanna learn
what pleases you.

136
00:10:38,074 --> 00:10:41,134
I wanna learn everything about you.

137
00:10:41,311 --> 00:10:43,336
Would you let me do that?

138
00:10:43,513 --> 00:10:45,708
Would you give me that job?

139
00:10:50,854 --> 00:10:52,822
I'm off in a half an hour.

140
00:10:54,524 --> 00:10:57,254
- Well, I'm in room...
- 217.

141
00:10:57,427 --> 00:10:59,361
217.

142
00:11:01,364 --> 00:11:03,229
See you there.

143
00:11:07,537 --> 00:11:10,062
Johnny, get on the horn
to Universal and Warners.

144
00:11:10,240 --> 00:11:12,105
I need two more cameras
by Saturday.

145
00:11:12,275 --> 00:11:15,039
Rent them if you can.
Steal them if you have to.

146
00:11:15,779 --> 00:11:17,872
Absotively, boss.

147
00:11:18,348 --> 00:11:19,576
Absotively.

148
00:11:21,251 --> 00:11:24,015
<i>Rumors coming from a lonely airstrip
out in Van Nuys.</i>

149
00:11:24,187 --> 00:11:27,486
<i>Sources whisper that young
Texas industrialist Howard Hughes...</i>

150
00:11:27,657 --> 00:11:30,057
<i>... won't stop pouring money
into his war epic.</i>

151
00:11:30,226 --> 00:11:31,625
<i>And do we mean epic!</i>

152
00:11:31,795 --> 00:11:34,628
<i>One hundred and thirty-seven pilots.
87 airplanes...</i>

153
00:11:34,798 --> 00:11:39,201
<i>... 35 cameramen. 2000 extras.
How long will it be before this picture...</i>

154
00:11:39,369 --> 00:11:41,599
<i>... ends up costing as
much as the real war?</i>

155
00:11:41,771 --> 00:11:44,001
Damn it.
Why the hell do they look so slow?

156
00:11:44,174 --> 00:11:47,769
This isn't what it was like up there.
They look like goddamn models!

157
00:11:56,152 --> 00:11:57,585
Son of a bitch.

158
00:11:58,888 --> 00:12:00,287
Howard?

159
00:12:02,859 --> 00:12:06,761
Without something standing
still behind the planes...

160
00:12:06,930 --> 00:12:09,490
...we've got no idea
of how fast we're moving.

161
00:12:09,666 --> 00:12:12,499
We got no sense of relative motion.

162
00:12:13,670 --> 00:12:16,332
Call UCLA.
Get me the best meteorologist they got.

163
00:12:16,506 --> 00:12:18,599
You get him here in an hour, all right?

164
00:12:21,978 --> 00:12:24,776
Hey. You want the good news
or the bad news?

165
00:12:24,948 --> 00:12:26,506
- Bad news, always.
- All right.

166
00:12:26,683 --> 00:12:29,880
We installed the 450 radial.
Struts won't take the vibration.

167
00:12:30,053 --> 00:12:33,853
Minute we fire her up, the struts
start cracking at the attach points.

168
00:12:34,090 --> 00:12:36,820
- Well, what's the good news?
- There isn't any.

169
00:12:37,227 --> 00:12:40,822
Goddamn it, Odie. If the 450's too big,
we figure something else out.

170
00:12:40,997 --> 00:12:43,966
We've done everything.
We've rebuilt her from top to toe.

171
00:12:44,134 --> 00:12:45,931
If we drain the fuel tank...

172
00:12:46,102 --> 00:12:49,765
...she might make 180 miles per hour.
- I want minimum 200, all right?

173
00:12:49,939 --> 00:12:52,806
I want a date with Theda Bara.
That ain't gonna happen.

174
00:12:52,976 --> 00:12:54,876
Oh, don't be so sure.

175
00:12:55,245 --> 00:12:59,113
If the struts won't sustain the engine
we need, we gotta get rid of the struts.

176
00:12:59,282 --> 00:13:01,341
No, then the top wing falls off.

177
00:13:04,053 --> 00:13:05,611
Then let it.

178
00:13:06,122 --> 00:13:07,589
What?

179
00:13:08,892 --> 00:13:10,917
Who says we need a top wing?

180
00:13:11,094 --> 00:13:13,153
I mean, who says we need anything?

181
00:13:15,331 --> 00:13:17,765
- A monoplane.
- A cantilevered monoplane, right?

182
00:13:17,934 --> 00:13:21,131
They're doing it in France.
To hell with the top wing and struts.

183
00:13:21,304 --> 00:13:23,704
- A 550 Wasp engine.
- One-hundred-octane fuel.

184
00:13:23,873 --> 00:13:27,172
- That would give us a horsepower of what?
- Seven hundred.

185
00:13:28,711 --> 00:13:32,841
We squeeze that to a thousand,
we got the fastest plane ever built.

186
00:13:35,652 --> 00:13:37,176
You know, I've gotta say...

187
00:13:37,353 --> 00:13:41,050
...we've already spent over $200,000
rebuilding this plane.

188
00:13:42,492 --> 00:13:44,084
To hell with it.

189
00:13:45,228 --> 00:13:46,593
Tear it up, Odie.

190
00:13:46,763 --> 00:13:48,128
Go on.

191
00:13:51,801 --> 00:13:53,132
Well...

192
00:13:56,072 --> 00:13:59,769
The cumulonimbus formations
about which you speak...

193
00:14:01,244 --> 00:14:03,371
...that look like...

194
00:14:03,546 --> 00:14:05,343
Giant breasts full of milk.

195
00:14:05,515 --> 00:14:07,244
I want clouds, damn it.

196
00:14:07,617 --> 00:14:09,209
Yes, clouds...

197
00:14:09,385 --> 00:14:13,185
...that look like
giant breasts full of milk...

198
00:14:13,356 --> 00:14:16,883
...cannot exactly be guaranteed
for any particular occasion.

199
00:14:17,060 --> 00:14:19,153
So you might have to...

200
00:14:20,463 --> 00:14:21,828
To wait.

201
00:14:23,933 --> 00:14:25,867
Then we'll wait.

202
00:14:26,836 --> 00:14:29,168
Look, whatever they pay
you at UCLA...

203
00:14:29,339 --> 00:14:32,934
...I'm doubling it, all right?
You work for me now. Find some clouds.

204
00:14:34,410 --> 00:14:35,775
Find some clouds.

205
00:14:36,446 --> 00:14:38,209
Find me some clouds!

206
00:14:38,381 --> 00:14:40,576
<i>Welcome to Hell's Angels.</i>

207
00:14:43,786 --> 00:14:45,014
Thank you.

208
00:14:53,663 --> 00:14:57,121
I've been to Chatsworth,
Santa Cruz, Encino, San Diego...

209
00:14:57,300 --> 00:15:01,168
...Riverside, Van Nuys and Bakersfield.
It has been eight months!

210
00:15:01,337 --> 00:15:03,134
Where are my goddamn clouds, huh?

211
00:15:03,306 --> 00:15:05,638
They move, Mr. Hughes!

212
00:15:05,808 --> 00:15:07,139
Clouds move.

213
00:15:07,310 --> 00:15:09,778
- That's what they do. They move!
- You see that?

214
00:15:09,946 --> 00:15:13,643
It is costing me $5271 a day...

215
00:15:13,816 --> 00:15:18,219
...to keep those planes on the ground.
You find me some goddamn clouds, huh?

216
00:15:25,662 --> 00:15:27,152
Nice day.

217
00:15:27,630 --> 00:15:29,530
Yeah, very funny.

218
00:15:29,799 --> 00:15:32,632
I got a call from Houston.
They're getting nervous.

219
00:15:32,802 --> 00:15:34,736
Stop showing them the damn bills.

220
00:15:34,904 --> 00:15:36,269
That would be illegal.

221
00:15:36,439 --> 00:15:38,669
Shit, no.
Maybe it's a little bit naughty.

222
00:15:38,841 --> 00:15:42,709
Hughes Tool is incorporated in Texas.
They have to see the bills.

223
00:15:44,113 --> 00:15:47,674
Incorporate a new division out here.
We'll call it Hughes Aircraft.

224
00:15:47,850 --> 00:15:52,412
- Do we need these rivets on the cowling?
- Yeah, or the reverse thrust would rip it off.

225
00:15:52,589 --> 00:15:55,285
They're gonna give me drag.
Do something about that.

226
00:15:55,458 --> 00:15:57,722
- Wind resistance on rivets?
- I want her slippery.

227
00:15:57,894 --> 00:16:00,920
There are tax consequences
to incorporating in California.

228
00:16:01,097 --> 00:16:03,565
- Just take care of it, would you?
- Mr. Hughes!

229
00:16:03,733 --> 00:16:05,530
Oakland!

230
00:16:05,702 --> 00:16:08,728
- We have clouds in Oakland!
- You mean it this time?

231
00:16:08,905 --> 00:16:10,463
Yes!

232
00:16:10,640 --> 00:16:13,734
Goddamn it, yes.
I can promise you.

233
00:16:13,910 --> 00:16:17,175
- Clouds in Oakland.
- All right, don't get all jittery now.

234
00:16:17,347 --> 00:16:18,746
Oakland!

235
00:16:19,649 --> 00:16:21,514
Oakland!

236
00:16:21,684 --> 00:16:24,915
We're going to Oakland!
Oakland.

237
00:17:01,090 --> 00:17:03,718
Down and to the left!

238
00:17:26,716 --> 00:17:28,707
That's perfect!

239
00:17:32,588 --> 00:17:36,991
That's right, Senator George.

240
00:17:37,160 --> 00:17:39,856
<i>Yes. Young Howard Hughes
has pulled it off!</i>

241
00:17:40,029 --> 00:17:43,430
<i>After two years. Hell's Angels
