- Oh. No.</i>

254
00:18:24,807 --> 00:18:26,775
<i>Yes.
We're gonna move up in the Bronx.</i>

255
00:18:26,943 --> 00:18:29,002
<i>Green grass.
A lot of people you know.</i>

256
00:18:29,178 --> 00:18:31,874
<i>The Ginsbergs.
The Guttenbergs and the Goldbergs.</i>

257
00:18:32,048 --> 00:18:34,744
<i>Oh. A whole lot of "bergs."
I don't know them all.</i>

258
00:18:35,351 --> 00:18:39,117
See, this is what the people want.
Silent pictures are yesterday's news.

259
00:18:39,288 --> 00:18:42,280
<i>So I figure we gotta reshoot
Hell's Angels for sound.</i>

260
00:18:44,694 --> 00:18:46,218
How much of it?

261
00:18:46,395 --> 00:18:48,659
All of it.
Before you ask, I'll tell you.

262
00:18:48,831 --> 00:18:51,698
An additional 1.7 million.
We got that much?

263
00:18:52,835 --> 00:18:56,100
- No!
- Well, we'll make it.

264
00:18:56,272 --> 00:18:58,001
Take care of that, would you?

265
00:18:58,174 --> 00:18:59,505
<i>Now. Get this.</i>

266
00:19:09,585 --> 00:19:11,746
<i>In the halls of 7000 Romaine...</i>

267
00:19:11,921 --> 00:19:14,355
<i>... it goes on day after day.
Month after month.</i>

268
00:19:14,524 --> 00:19:18,221
<i>Howard Hughes is now editing
some 25 miles of film.</i>

269
00:19:19,629 --> 00:19:24,225
<i>Heck. I say release it now and give
the world its first 560-hour movie.</i>

270
00:19:24,400 --> 00:19:28,666
Pat, Mr. Hughes needs this reel
in the projection room right now!

271
00:19:29,539 --> 00:19:31,131
<i>Enough is enough. Mr. Hughes.</i>

272
00:19:31,307 --> 00:19:34,504
<i>Are you ever gonna let us
actually see this epic of yours?</i>

273
00:19:34,677 --> 00:19:36,167
Hurry up!

274
00:19:57,166 --> 00:19:58,565
- Who is it?
- Noah.

275
00:19:58,734 --> 00:20:00,395
Come on in.

276
00:20:01,971 --> 00:20:04,565
I've been on the phone
to Houston for three hours.

277
00:20:04,740 --> 00:20:07,732
- We're fixing every goddamn book we have.
- Wait, wait.

278
00:20:08,678 --> 00:20:12,079
Yeah. Run reel 10 again.
I think we're duplicating a shot here.

279
00:20:12,248 --> 00:20:16,082
And tell Jimmy I want
10 chocolate chip cookies, all right?

280
00:20:16,252 --> 00:20:19,119
Medium chips,
none too close to the outside.

281
00:20:19,288 --> 00:20:20,778
Got it?

282
00:20:20,957 --> 00:20:23,289
You remember
that goddamn shot from reel 10?

283
00:20:23,459 --> 00:20:26,053
No. I don't remember
anything from reel 10.

284
00:20:26,229 --> 00:20:28,390
I don't know what reel 10 is.

285
00:20:28,564 --> 00:20:31,829
I'm a businessman, Howard.
And so are you.

286
00:20:32,001 --> 00:20:33,798
Now, look.

287
00:20:33,970 --> 00:20:35,437
This has been a great ride.

288
00:20:35,605 --> 00:20:37,539
We've had a hell of a lot of fun.

289
00:20:37,940 --> 00:20:41,603
But you're losing
$25,000 a day doing this.

290
00:20:41,911 --> 00:20:43,811
Every day.

291
00:20:49,385 --> 00:20:52,218
So, what are my options?

292
00:20:53,789 --> 00:20:56,519
Well, this time I don't know
that you have any.

293
00:20:56,692 --> 00:20:59,126
I'm afraid you gotta close it down.

294
00:20:59,896 --> 00:21:01,488
Dig your way out.

295
00:21:08,170 --> 00:21:10,161
I'm sorry, Howard.

296
00:21:10,740 --> 00:21:12,537
I truly am.

297
00:21:19,916 --> 00:21:21,508
<i>Reel 10. Mr. Hughes.</i>

298
00:21:27,556 --> 00:21:29,581
Mortgage Tool Co.

299
00:21:30,493 --> 00:21:35,590
- Every asset. You heard me.
- Lf you do that, you could lose everything.

300
00:21:35,765 --> 00:21:37,323
Well, I won't.

301
00:21:40,469 --> 00:21:41,936
I won't.

302
00:21:43,406 --> 00:21:45,203
All right.

303
00:21:46,409 --> 00:21:48,036
I'll get into it.

304
00:21:49,412 --> 00:21:50,970
Thanks, Noah.

305
00:22:26,082 --> 00:22:29,813
<i>More than half a million souls lining
the curb of Hollywood Boulevard.</i>

306
00:22:29,986 --> 00:22:31,613
<i>Look at the automobiles!</i>

307
00:22:31,787 --> 00:22:35,655
<i>There are 45.000 cars here.
Making it the greatest traffic jam ever seen.</i>

308
00:22:35,825 --> 00:22:38,225
<i>Howard Hughes must have
a lump in his throat.</i>

309
00:22:38,394 --> 00:22:42,490
<i>Six months after the stock market crashes
and after three pilots' deaths...</i>

310
00:22:42,665 --> 00:22:45,634
<i>... he's finally unveiling his
$4 million baby doll.</i>

311
00:22:45,801 --> 00:22:50,101
<i>It's the most expensive movie ever made.
Nothing five-and-dime for our Mr. Hughes.</i>

312
00:22:50,272 --> 00:22:53,571
<i>Nothing like tonight has ever been
seen before. And I can say...</i>

313
00:22:53,743 --> 00:22:55,404
<i>... it will never be seen again.</i>

314
00:22:55,578 --> 00:22:59,571
<i>Five hundred thousand people are crowding
the streets to get a glimpse of the stars.</i>

315
00:22:59,749 --> 00:23:02,445
<i>Three companies of Marines
were called to assist...</i>

316
00:23:02,618 --> 00:23:06,054
<i>... the 250 special police who are
handling this enormous crowd...</i>

317
00:23:06,222 --> 00:23:07,746
<i>This is an industry town.</i>

318
00:23:07,923 --> 00:23:10,824
<i>And nobody but nobody
makes a movie outside a studio.</i>

319
00:23:10,993 --> 00:23:14,485
<i>Some Hollywood insiders over
at the Brown Derby may be laughing...</i>

320
00:23:14,663 --> 00:23:16,130
<i>And now. I think...</i>

321
00:23:16,298 --> 00:23:19,131
<i>Yes. Yes. I can see
Mr. Hughes' car arriving now.</i>

322
00:23:19,301 --> 00:23:22,270
<i>Mr. Hughes escorts
the lovely starlet Jean Harlow.</i>

323
00:23:22,438 --> 00:23:26,431
<i>He discovered her for this picture.
And we think her platinum blond locks...</i>

324
00:23:26,609 --> 00:23:30,875
<i>... and hot-jazz. Baby-doll style
are gonna make her a big star.</i>

325
00:23:39,822 --> 00:23:42,120
Howard! Howard!

326
00:23:48,664 --> 00:23:50,529
Over here!

327
00:23:57,106 --> 00:24:01,338
- This way, boss. Right over there.
- Mr. Hughes, how about a word?

328
00:24:01,544 --> 00:24:04,012
Big night for you, Mr. Hughes.

329
00:24:05,948 --> 00:24:08,576
Big night for you tonight.

330
00:24:08,751 --> 00:24:11,083
Very big. Very big.

331
00:24:11,253 --> 00:24:14,950
Tell us what it was like
making this fabulous picture.

332
00:24:16,792 --> 00:24:18,555
Yes.

333
00:24:18,727 --> 00:24:20,126
Yeah.

334
00:24:20,296 --> 00:24:22,924
So 4 million clams
from your own pocket.

335
00:24:23,099 --> 00:24:24,726
Nervous how the flick will fly?

336
00:24:28,304 --> 00:24:31,603
Big night. You enjoy the show.

337
00:24:32,108 --> 00:24:37,478
<i>Yes, well, let me present the feminine
star of this spectacle, Hell's Angels...</i>

338
00:24:37,646 --> 00:24:40,240
...Miss Jean Harlow.
- Thank you.

339
00:24:40,416 --> 00:24:43,385
I would like to use this occasion
to thank Mr. Hughes...

340
00:24:43,552 --> 00:24:46,851
...for the opportunity he gave me.
Thank you.

341
00:24:47,022 --> 00:24:50,389
Thank you!
Now I'd like to ask Roscoe Arbuckle...

342
00:24:50,559 --> 00:24:53,528
...to introduce
his pet lion cub, Gilmore.

343
00:24:53,696 --> 00:24:56,358
What's the matter with you?
Can't remember my name?

344
00:24:56,532 --> 00:25:00,525
I'm sorry. Roscoe Turner,
and this would be Gilmore.

345
00:25:43,646 --> 00:25:45,307
It's going! It's going!

346
00:25:46,982 --> 00:25:50,418
Murder! That's what this
dirty, rotten politician war is, murder!

347
00:25:50,586 --> 00:25:52,053
You know it as well as I do.

348
00:26:29,825 --> 00:26:31,417
Stand up, slim, take a bow.

349
00:26:45,040 --> 00:26:47,270
Reel four played too long.
Too many coughs.

350
00:26:47,443 --> 00:26:51,402
Get the team out of the party and
to the office. I wanna cut a few shots.

351
00:26:51,580 --> 00:26:53,810
Oh, find Glenn.
Somebody write this down.

352
00:26:53,983 --> 00:26:55,211
Flush rivets.
Got that?

353
00:26:55,384 --> 00:26:57,079
- Flush rivets.
- Flush rivets.

354
00:26:57,253 --> 00:26:58,777
Lickety-split, boss.

355
00:26:59,021 --> 00:27:00,648
Here he is! Here he is!

356
00:27:02,725 --> 00:27:04,625
<i>Variety says. "This one won't miss!"</i>

357
00:27:04,793 --> 00:27:08,058
<i>- Magnificently photographed!
- Awesome beyond description!</i>

358
00:27:08,230 --> 00:27:11,825
<i>The most extraordinary output
to emerge from a motion-picture studio.</i>

359
00:27:12,001 --> 00:27:14,936
<i>Not for a long time have I seen
anything as enthralling.</i>

360
00:27:15,104 --> 00:27:18,130
<i>It costs 4 million dollars
and has 4 million thrills!</i>

361
00:27:18,307 --> 00:27:20,605
<i>- Majestically...
- Most epic picture of its time!</i>

362
00:28:16,065 --> 00:28:19,034
A lighter shade. I don't want
to look like Boris Karloff.

363
00:28:19,201 --> 00:28:20,793
If you know what I mean.

364
00:28:22,738 --> 00:28:26,674
I read in the magazines
that you play golf.

365
00:28:26,842 --> 00:28:28,503
On occasion.

366
00:28:28,677 --> 00:28:30,907
Well, how about nine holes?

367
00:28:33,015 --> 00:28:35,176
Now, Mr. Hughes?

368
00:28:35,851 --> 00:28:38,581
If it would be convenient, Miss Hepburn.

369
00:29:01,143 --> 00:29:04,601
You're not extending
enough on your follow-through.

370
00:29:04,780 --> 00:29:07,715
Follow-through
is everything in golf, just like life.

371
00:29:07,883 --> 00:29:09,180
Don't you find?

372
00:29:09,351 --> 00:29:11,376
<i>Saw your Scarface picture.</i>

373
00:29:11,553 --> 00:29:12,850
- Violent.
- Realistic.

374
00:29:13,021 --> 00:29:15,353
Movies are movies, Howard.
Not life.

375
00:29:15,524 --> 00:29:17,219
Now the stage.

376
00:29:17,393 --> 00:29:18,621
The stage is real.

377
00:29:18,794 --> 00:29:22,787
Real flesh and blood. Human beings
right out there in front of you, buster.

378
00:29:22,965 --> 00:29:25,934
Can't look away. Can't munch popcorn.
That would be rude.

379
00:29:26,101 --> 00:29:27,363
Do you like the theater?

380
00:29:27,669 --> 00:29:30,160
- No.
- Oh, I adore the theater.

381
00:29:30,339 --> 00:29:32,500
Only alive on-stage.
I'll teach you.

382
00:29:32,674 --> 00:29:36,610
We'll see some Ibsen. If the Republicans
haven't outlawed him by now.

383
00:29:36,779 --> 00:29:39,805
You're not a Republican, are you?
How did you vote in '32?

384
00:29:39,982 --> 00:29:43,440
- Well, I didn't.
- You must! It's your sacred franchise.

385
00:29:47,322 --> 00:29:50,086
Heard you were wooing Ginger Rogers.
What about that?

386
00:29:50,259 --> 00:29:52,591
She's just a friend.

387
00:29:52,761 --> 00:29:54,456
Men can't be friends with women.

388
00:29:54,630 --> 00:29:56,689
They must possess them
or leave them be.

389
00:29:56,865 --> 00:29:59,993
It's a primitive urge from caveman days.
It's all in Darwin.

390
00:30:00,169 --> 00:30:05,505
Hunt the flesh, kill the flesh, eat the flesh.
That's the male sex all over.

391
00:30:06,175 --> 00:30:07,540
Excuse me?

392
00:30:08,343 --> 00:30:11,335
Well, if you're deaf,
you must own up to it.

393
00:30:11,613 --> 00:30:13,547
Get a hearing aid.
Or see my father.

394
00:30:13,715 --> 00:30:17,378
He's a urologist, but it's all tied up
inside the body, don't you find?

395
00:30:17,719 --> 00:30:19,186
Me, I keep healthy.

396
00:30:19,354 --> 00:30:21,481
I take seven showers a day
to keep clean.

397
00:30:21,657 --> 00:30:24,990
Also because I am what's so
vulgarly referred to as "outdoorsy."

398
00:30:25,160 --> 00:30:29,153
I'm not outdoorsy.
I'm athletic. I sweat.

399
00:30:29,331 --> 00:30:32,095
There it is.
Now we both know the sordid truth.

400
00:30:32,267 --> 00:30:34,735
I sweat and you're deaf.

401
00:30:34,903 --> 00:30:37,770
Aren't we a fine pair of misfits?

402
00:30:41,343 --> 00:30:43,208
Three.

403
00:30:50,752 --> 00:30:52,583
Noble effort.

404
00:30:54,957 --> 00:30:57,653
So I suppose you're
wooing me now?

405
00:30:58,327 --> 00:31:00,318
Oh, well.

406
00:31:19,381 --> 00:31:20,871
Not enough.

407
00:31:21,450 --> 00:31:24,476
Not enough.
These rivets have to be completely flush.

408
00:31:24,653 --> 00:31:27,554
I want every screw and joint countersunk.

409
00:31:27,789 --> 00:31:30,587
I want no wind resistance
on the fuselage.

410
00:31:30,759 --> 00:31:33,057
She has got to be clean, Odie.

411
00:31:33,228 --> 00:31:34,991
- Clean. Understand?
- Okay, Howard.

412
00:31:35,163 --> 00:31:36,960
I don't know
what else to tell you.

413
00:31:38,033 --> 00:31:41,594
- What do you got for me?
- The thing is, TWA needs a new plane.

414
00:31:41,770 --> 00:31:44,398
- A modern plane.
- Oh, yeah? What kind of plane?

415
00:31:44,573 --> 00:31:46,803
Okay. The DC-3 has 21 daytime seats...

416
00:31:46,975 --> 00:31:49,409
...and 14 overnight berths.
- Something bigger?

417
00:31:50,746 --> 00:31:53,112
Try 50 seats with
a ceiling of 12,000 feet.

418
00:31:53,282 --> 00:31:55,512
No. No, 20,000.

419
00:31:55,884 --> 00:31:58,011
Think about it.
What does 20,000 feet give you?

420
00:31:58,186 --> 00:32:00,780
- Less turbulence.
- Because it's above the weather.

421
00:32:00,956 --> 00:32:03,322
Jack, we wanna fly
above the weather.

422
00:32:03,492 --> 00:32:07,053
Only 1 percent of the American population
has set foot on an airliner.

423
00:32:07,229 --> 00:32:09,993
Why? Because they're scared to death.
They should be.

424
00:32:10,165 --> 00:32:12,759
I mean, 7000 feet is bumpy as shit.
You know that.

425
00:32:12,935 --> 00:32:15,426
We build a plane
that flies above the weather...

426
00:32:15,604 --> 00:32:19,370
...we could get every man, woman
and child in this country to feel safe.

427
00:32:19,541 --> 00:32:24,035
An airplane with the ability to fly into
the substratosphere across the country.

428
00:32:24,212 --> 00:32:26,043
Across the world.

429
00:32:26,214 --> 00:32:28,307
Now that is the future.

430
00:32:28,750 --> 00:32:29,978
- You with me?
- Yeah.

431
00:32:30,152 --> 00:32:34,088
I don't wanna get into this
if your board doesn't have the balls for it.

432
00:32:34,256 --> 00:32:36,554
- Would they support us?
- I don't know.

433
00:32:36,725 --> 00:32:38,955
- What's your financial picture?
- Not great.

434
00:32:39,127 --> 00:32:41,288
- Last year's deficit?
- 770,000.

435
00:32:41,463 --> 00:32:44,159
- What's it selling at?
- About 8 dollars a share.

436
00:32:44,333 --> 00:32:46,062
That's the lowest it's been, huh?

437
00:32:48,036 --> 00:32:49,503
I could do that.

438
00:32:49,671 --> 00:32:51,161
- Do what?
- Buy it.

439
00:32:51,340 --> 00:32:54,002
- You wanna buy the airline?
- For crying out loud...

440
00:32:54,176 --> 00:32:58,078
...we don't want pencil pushers getting
in the way of us making our plane.

441
00:32:58,246 --> 00:33:02,080
Give me brass tacks, now. What does
controlling interest in TWA cost me?

442
00:33:03,118 --> 00:33:04,517
Call it 15 million.

443
00:33:06,922 --> 00:33:09,083
That is a chunk of change, huh?

444
00:33:12,527 --> 00:33:14,358
You call Noah Dietrich.

445
00:33:14,529 --> 00:33:16,497
You have him start buying.

446
00:33:16,665 --> 00:33:17,927
Howard, hold on.

447
00:33:18,100 --> 00:33:21,126
Are you sure?
You wanna think about it for five minutes?

448
00:33:21,303 --> 00:33:25,137
Hell, Jack, I got a tiger by the tail here.
I ain't gonna let it go.

449
00:33:33,949 --> 00:33:35,678
Good evening, Mr. Hughes.

450
00:33:35,851 --> 00:33:38,217
Welcome. Your table is ready.

451
00:33:39,388 --> 00:33:40,912
How goes the aviation?

452
00:33:41,089 --> 00:33:44,058
- Oh, just fine, Pete.
- I'm so glad.

453
00:33:46,395 --> 00:33:47,726
Good evening, Mr. Hughes.

454
00:33:47,896 --> 00:33:49,124
- Madame.
- It's "miss."

455
00:33:49,297 --> 00:33:51,731
Miss. The usual, Mr. Hughes?

456
00:33:51,900 --> 00:33:54,027
- Please.
- May I recommend for the lady...

457
00:33:54,202 --> 00:33:57,694
...our clementine soup followed
by roast duck with currant glaze...

458
00:33:57,873 --> 00:34:00,842
...and poached pears in rose sauce.
It's truly divine.

459
00:34:01,009 --> 00:34:02,499
Yeah. That sounds fine.

460
00:34:04,680 --> 00:34:07,410
Your kind of joint, is it?

461
00:34:08,550 --> 00:34:10,108
Wouldn't have thought.

462
00:34:10,285 --> 00:34:13,482
They're open late.
I go to a hot-dog stand on La Cienega too.

463
00:34:13,655 --> 00:34:16,317
- They're open till about 4.
- Are they?

464
00:34:18,360 --> 00:34:20,191
How marvelous.

465
00:34:36,044 --> 00:34:37,671
Howard! Howard!

466
00:34:38,647 --> 00:34:41,411
Hi! Son of a gun.

467
00:34:41,583 --> 00:34:45,417
Kate, this is Johnny Meyer.
I suppose you could call him my press agent.

468
00:34:45,587 --> 00:34:47,851
<i>- Pleased to meet you. Loved Alice Adams.
- You're too kind.</i>

469
00:34:48,023 --> 00:34:50,719
- I'm sure you know Errol, right?
- Mr. Flynn. Yes.

470
00:34:50,892 --> 00:34:55,761
Kate. Kate. Kate of the clenched-jawed
Hepburns. Enchanting as always.

471
00:34:55,931 --> 00:34:58,627
You should use Lux on your hands,
by the way. I do.

472
00:34:58,800 --> 00:35:00,961
You and Howard
ought to cook up a picture.

473
00:35:01,136 --> 00:35:03,661
Costar with Errol.
I could sell that in spades.

474
00:35:03,839 --> 00:35:06,034
That would be marvelous. Howard?

475
00:35:06,641 --> 00:35:10,372
<i>I think not.
Don't you read Variety, Mr. Meyer?</i>

476
00:35:10,545 --> 00:35:14,242
Well, I'm box-office poison.
I'm on the outs, the skids, the doldrums.

477
00:35:14,416 --> 00:35:17,783
Washed-up, day-old fish
not worth the eating, so they tell me.

478
00:35:17,953 --> 00:35:21,787
Hell with them. Hell with them, my dear.
Soulless pricks to a man, right?

479
00:35:21,957 --> 00:35:25,984
Johnny tells me you're thinking about
doing a Western, of all goddamn things.

480
00:35:30,065 --> 00:35:32,829
Are you making a Western, Howard?

481
00:35:33,034 --> 00:35:35,798
<i>Yeah. Making a Western.
I'm gonna call it The Outlaw.</i>

482
00:35:35,971 --> 00:35:38,132
Yeah. And you know
what it's about? S-E-X.

483
00:35:38,306 --> 00:35:41,002
- It's all about S-E-X.
- It's a Western.

484
00:35:41,176 --> 00:35:44,077
You can't have fornication in a Western.
It isn't done.

485
00:35:44,246 --> 00:35:46,043
It's not real sex, it's movie sex.

486
00:35:46,214 --> 00:35:49,877
<i>What Scarface did for the gangster picture,
The Outlaw will do for the Western.</i>

487
00:35:50,051 --> 00:35:52,918
Put the sex and guts and blood
up there on the screen.

488
00:35:53,088 --> 00:35:55,113
- Have you seen my cigarettes?
- Don't mind us.

489
00:35:55,290 --> 00:35:58,691
New York cut steak, 12 peas,
bottle of milk with the cap on.

490
00:35:58,860 --> 00:36:02,091
- You can't afford your own cigarettes?
- Jack has all my money.

491
00:36:02,264 --> 00:36:06,564
I hope your food isn't getting cold
at your table somewhere or something.

492
00:36:06,735 --> 00:36:09,033
No, no. We're here all night.
Don't worry.

493
00:36:09,204 --> 00:36:14,733
Now, Howard. Now, Howard. If you're
seriously talking about putting carnality...

494
00:36:14,910 --> 00:36:19,574
...back on the silver screen, you must swear
to let me in on the casting session.

495
00:36:22,717 --> 00:36:27,586
- I have an eye for talent. Isn't that right?
- You ought to give up prancing in tights...

496
00:36:27,756 --> 00:36:31,351
...be a talent scout.
- That prancing paid for my new yacht.

497
00:36:31,526 --> 00:36:34,984
You must all come sailing with me.
Catalina. What do you say?

498
00:36:35,163 --> 00:36:38,326
- Catalina. Sounds grand. Yeah.
- I've even managed to coax...

499
00:36:38,500 --> 00:36:42,368
...the luscious Miss De Havilland
and her equally luscious sister to come.

500
00:36:42,537 --> 00:36:47,406
Though I fear their mother will insist on
coming, to preserve their questionable virtue.

501
00:36:47,576 --> 00:36:51,774
We shall assault these twin monuments
of pristine Britannic beauty nonetheless.

502
00:36:51,947 --> 00:36:54,006
- What do you say, Howard?
- Yeah?

503
00:36:54,416 --> 00:36:56,577
- Yeah. Yeah.
- Yeah?

504
00:37:00,889 --> 00:37:02,186
I gotta go.

505
00:37:03,058 --> 00:37:06,585
If you'll excuse us, we have...
We have to be somewhere.

506
00:37:06,928 --> 00:37:09,396
You are somewhere, Howard,
you madman.

507
00:37:09,564 --> 00:37:12,590
- Somewhere else. Excuse us.
- Charmed, gentlemen.

508
00:37:12,767 --> 00:37:16,396
Do help yourself to the poached pears.
I hear they're divine.

509
00:37:17,038 --> 00:37:19,802
Well. Howard Hughes,
ladies and gentlemen.

510
00:37:20,675 --> 00:37:22,006
Was that meant for me?

511
00:37:22,177 --> 00:37:25,544
My hero. God, all that
Hollywood talk bores me silly.

512
00:37:25,714 --> 00:37:28,683
As if there aren't more important things,
like Mussolini.

513
00:37:28,850 --> 00:37:32,786
- Where are we going, by the way?
- Do you feel like a little adventure?

514
00:37:32,954 --> 00:37:34,888
Do your worst, Mr. Hughes.

515
00:37:35,056 --> 00:37:39,254
- Think you own this place, you limey bastard?
- I'm a Tasmanian bastard, you prick.

516
00:37:39,427 --> 00:37:41,827
- Thataway, Errol.
- Let me at him!

517
00:38:15,430 --> 00:38:18,126
That's Mr. Mayer's house right there.

518
00:38:18,300 --> 00:38:20,200
Do you know where Jack Warner lives?

519
00:38:29,477 --> 00:38:33,277
- What's that on the steering wheel?
- Cellophane.

520
00:38:33,448 --> 00:38:37,316
If you had any idea of the crap
that people carry around on their hands.

521
00:38:37,852 --> 00:38:39,479
What kind of crap?

522
00:38:40,188 --> 00:38:41,849
You don't wanna know.

523
00:38:47,128 --> 00:38:49,062
Hold on to the wheel for a bit.

524
00:38:57,138 --> 00:39:00,266
That's too hard. Relax your hand.
Relax your hand.

525
00:39:05,947 --> 00:39:10,907
You see, you gotta feel the vibration
of the engine through your fingertips.

526
00:39:11,086 --> 00:39:14,146
- Do you feel that?
- Yes.

527
00:39:16,758 --> 00:39:18,419
Well, that's good.

528
00:39:19,060 --> 00:39:20,755
Golly!

529
00:39:25,166 --> 00:39:26,963
Well, she's all yours.

530
00:39:27,202 --> 00:39:30,865
- Where are you going?!
- I think there's some milk back here.

531
00:39:31,873 --> 00:39:34,671
- You just keep us steady, now.
- All right.

532
00:39:53,661 --> 00:39:55,492
- Howard.
- Yeah?

533
00:39:55,663 --> 00:39:58,632
There's a rather alarming mountain
heading our way.

534
00:39:58,800 --> 00:40:00,995
Pull back on the wheel a smidge.
Go on.

535
00:40:05,840 --> 00:40:08,434
Golly!

536
00:40:13,982 --> 00:40:19,147
I don't think I've ever met someone
who actually uses the word "golly."

537
00:40:26,394 --> 00:40:28,862
You all right?
Do you want me to take over?

538
00:40:29,030 --> 00:40:31,021
Just when I'm getting the hang of it?

539
00:40:36,404 --> 00:40:40,101
- You want some milk?
- Oh, please.

540
00:41:02,030 --> 00:41:04,260
Utterly smashing!
We'll do it again.

541
00:41:04,432 --> 00:41:07,595
I'm free Wednesday.
It's a little early for golf, though.

542
00:41:07,769 --> 00:41:10,033
Oh, no, no. I live right there.

543
00:41:10,538 --> 00:41:13,098
- Feel like a drink?
- Lead on.

544
00:41:14,309 --> 00:41:17,506
Now, that makes
for a challenging par four.

545
00:41:17,745 --> 00:41:21,442
My decorator
picked out the wallpaper and such.

546
00:41:22,083 --> 00:41:24,142
He's queer as a bedbug.

547
00:41:24,319 --> 00:41:27,049
But I just hate this room.

548
00:41:27,355 --> 00:41:29,186
Gives me the willies.

549
00:41:29,691 --> 00:41:33,787
<i>Like I'm about to be swallowed up
by the latest issue of Town & Country.</i>

550
00:41:42,437 --> 00:41:44,200
What room do you like?

551
00:41:45,473 --> 00:41:46,963
My study.

552
00:41:49,344 --> 00:41:51,005
Take me there.

553
00:42:07,362 --> 00:42:10,388
You are the tallest woman I know.

554
00:42:11,332 --> 00:42:15,428
And all sharp elbows and knees.
Beware.

555
00:42:37,959 --> 00:42:41,019
Will you fly me to work tomorrow?

556
00:42:43,631 --> 00:42:45,826
It is tomorrow.

557
00:43:38,620 --> 00:43:42,386
Keep your eye on the fuel. She's got
a minimum to keep her weight down.

558
00:43:42,557 --> 00:43:45,583
Two runs. That's it.
After that, you're flying on vapors.

559
00:43:45,760 --> 00:43:48,524
And then you crash and you die.
Give her easy flying.

560
00:43:48,696 --> 00:43:51,995
Don't worry about speed
and don't think about the record today.

561
00:43:52,166 --> 00:43:55,624
I wish you'd let someone else take her.
You've got 20 test pilots.

562
00:43:55,803 --> 00:44:00,137
Hell, why should I let someone else
have all the fun? See you in a bit.

563
00:44:21,095 --> 00:44:22,858
Contact!

564
00:45:52,487 --> 00:45:53,715
339.

565
00:45:55,823 --> 00:45:57,688
Goddamn!

566
00:46:19,414 --> 00:46:20,938
347.

567
00:46:22,383 --> 00:46:23,680
Son of a bitch!

568
00:46:56,050 --> 00:46:58,610
- 352.
- 352!

569
00:46:59,854 --> 00:47:01,082
Good girl.

570
00:47:10,865 --> 00:47:12,560
Damn it!

571
00:47:16,370 --> 00:47:18,497
Goddamn it!

572
00:47:18,940 --> 00:47:21,170
- Oh, God!
- There goes our meal ticket.

573
00:47:21,342 --> 00:47:22,832
Come on!

574
00:48:02,984 --> 00:48:04,417
Howard!

575
00:48:04,585 --> 00:48:06,746
- Howard!
- How did we do?

576
00:48:07,855 --> 00:48:10,187
352 on the last run.

577
00:48:11,959 --> 00:48:13,586
She'll go faster.

578
00:48:14,161 --> 00:48:15,788
Country mouse!

579
00:48:16,564 --> 00:48:19,965
- Kate! Katie!
- Upstairs, city mouse.

580
00:48:22,921 --> 00:48:25,822
Hello.
Good Lord, what happened to you?

581
00:48:25,991 --> 00:48:28,221
Oh, nothing. A hard landing.
I cut my foot.

582
00:48:28,394 --> 00:48:31,420
Sit down. I'll take care of it.
You tell me everything.

583
00:48:31,597 --> 00:48:35,431
You cannot imagine what it was like, Katie.
You cannot imagine the speed.

584
00:48:35,601 --> 00:48:38,764
- She was like a winged bullet up there.
- What did she make?

585
00:48:38,937 --> 00:48:43,101
Oh, around 352.

586
00:48:50,082 --> 00:48:51,549
You did it!

587
00:48:52,885 --> 00:48:54,750
Fastest man on the planet.

588
00:48:54,920 --> 00:48:58,151
Hot dog! I'm so proud of you.

589
00:48:58,323 --> 00:49:00,314
- She did it, baby.
- You knew she would.

590
00:49:00,492 --> 00:49:03,461
Oh, she was fine. She was just fine.

591
00:49:04,663 --> 00:49:06,221
Now let me see your foot.

592
00:49:06,465 --> 00:49:07,762
Yeah.

593
00:49:08,467 --> 00:49:12,028
- Good God! You're covered in blood.
- Oh, no. That's just beet juice.

594
00:49:12,204 --> 00:49:14,365
- I crashed into a beet field.
- What?

595
00:49:14,540 --> 00:49:16,735
Yeah, I crashed in a beet field.

596
00:49:19,945 --> 00:49:22,038
Let me get you cleaned up.

597
00:49:23,048 --> 00:49:27,576
- Heavens, what is this? Electrical tape?
- Yeah. Odie just sort of slammed it on there.

598
00:49:28,620 --> 00:49:33,648
But all I could think about
was getting home to see you.

599
00:49:38,363 --> 00:49:41,230
I am so proud of you.

600
00:49:45,771 --> 00:49:48,137
Now, this is gonna sting a little bit.

601
00:49:48,307 --> 00:49:52,107
Oh, this is useless.
Come to the bathroom.

602
00:49:53,345 --> 00:49:56,212
- Don't get beet juice on the carpet.
- I won't, I won't.

603
00:49:56,381 --> 00:49:59,043
- Too hot!
- Don't be a baby.

604
00:50:00,719 --> 00:50:03,552
Was the press there?

605
00:50:04,490 --> 00:50:05,752
Some.

606
00:50:05,991 --> 00:50:11,088
But they're calling everyone.
Should be on the wires by now.

607
00:50:19,705 --> 00:50:21,263
What is it?

608
00:50:23,976 --> 00:50:25,568
Kate?

609
00:50:28,814 --> 00:50:31,908
I've been famous,
for better or worse...

610
00:50:32,451 --> 00:50:34,419
...for a long time now...

611
00:50:34,586 --> 00:50:38,920
...and I wonder if you know what it...

612
00:50:39,558 --> 00:50:41,355
...really means.

613
00:50:42,528 --> 00:50:45,622
<i>Yeah. I had my fair share
of press on Hell's Angels.</i>

614
00:50:46,398 --> 00:50:48,195
I'm used to it.

615
00:50:50,135 --> 00:50:51,830
Are you?

616
00:50:55,507 --> 00:50:57,270
Howard, we're...

617
00:51:00,212 --> 00:51:02,646
We're not like everyone else.

618
00:51:04,650 --> 00:51:09,587
Too many acute angles.
Too many eccentricities.

619
00:51:10,355 --> 00:51:13,222
We have to be very careful not to...

620
00:51:14,526 --> 00:51:18,360
...let people in,
or they'll make us into freaks.

621
00:51:19,565 --> 00:51:24,127
Kate, they can't get in here.
We're safe.

622
00:51:25,837 --> 00:51:27,737
They can always get in.

623
00:51:29,908 --> 00:51:33,309
When my brother killed himself...

624
00:51:34,479 --> 00:51:37,039
...there were photographers
at the funeral.

625
00:51:38,283 --> 00:51:40,513
There's no decency to it.

626
00:51:52,965 --> 00:51:55,024
You know, sometimes I...

627
00:51:58,770 --> 00:52:00,931
I get these feelings, Katie.

628
00:52:05,911 --> 00:52:08,471
I get these ideas, these...

629
00:52:11,316 --> 00:52:13,910
...crazy ideas about...

630
00:52:16,355 --> 00:52:18,721
...things that may not...

631
00:52:19,992 --> 00:52:22,859
Things that may not really be there.

632
00:52:23,528 --> 00:52:25,052
Yeah.

633
00:52:31,737 --> 00:52:34,501
Sometimes I truly fear that I'm...

634
00:52:36,541 --> 00:52:38,509
...Iosing my mind.

635
00:52:46,084 --> 00:52:47,949
And if I did, it would...

636
00:52:51,056 --> 00:52:53,422
It'd be like flying blind.

637
00:53:01,566 --> 00:53:03,227
You understand?

638
00:53:07,406 --> 00:53:10,204
You taught me to fly, Howard.

639
00:53:13,178 --> 00:53:15,169
I'll take the wheel.

640
00:53:31,096 --> 00:53:35,123
<i>Smashing all records. Howard Hughes
outdoes Jules Verne's wildest dreams.</i>

641
00:53:35,434 --> 00:53:38,699
<i>Around the world from New York
to New York in four days.</i>

642
00:53:38,870 --> 00:53:41,805
<i>Even beating Wiley Post's mark
by over three days.</i>

643
00:53:41,973 --> 00:53:45,204
<i>New aviation history is written
when his Lockheed monoplane...</i>

644
00:53:45,377 --> 00:53:48,369
<i>... returns swiftly and safely.
A daring aviator.</i>

645
00:53:48,814 --> 00:53:51,476
<i>A true pioneer of the world's airways.</i>

646
00:53:51,650 --> 00:53:55,643
<i>From New York to Paris. He cuts Lindbergh's
time in half. Then on to Moscow.</i>

647
00:53:55,821 --> 00:54:00,383
<i>Thirty-five hours out of New York.
He roars across Siberia's trackless wastes.</i>

648
00:54:00,559 --> 00:54:05,189
<i>Sixty hours out of New York. He heads
for Alaska. Most hazardous hop of all.</i>

649
00:54:05,363 --> 00:54:07,763
<i>Continuing the terrific pace.
He comes home...</i>

650
00:54:07,933 --> 00:54:10,265
<i>... bringing new laurels
to American aviation.</i>

651
00:54:11,603 --> 00:54:14,868
<i>Howard Hughes and his crew
may find more worlds to conquer...</i>

652
00:54:21,680 --> 00:54:26,242
You won't believe this. It just came over the
wires. Hughes has bought control of TWA.

653
00:54:28,987 --> 00:54:31,854
I thought Mr. Hughes
was flying around the world.

654
00:54:32,057 --> 00:54:35,458
Apparently he did it while he was flying,
over the radio.

655
00:54:42,667 --> 00:54:45,966
I have heard some disquieting rumors
about Mr. Hughes.

656
00:54:47,539 --> 00:54:50,975
I'd like to know everything
there is to know about Mr. Hughes.

657
00:54:53,411 --> 00:54:55,641
I'd like you to attend to that for me.

658
00:54:56,648 --> 00:54:58,275
Thoroughly.

659
00:54:58,850 --> 00:55:01,284
<i>The Pantages is glittering tonight.</i>

660
00:55:01,453 --> 00:55:04,286
- Howard!
- Right over here. This way, over to the left.

661
00:55:04,456 --> 00:55:07,118
- Mr. Hughes, how was your flight?
- Miss Hepburn!

662
00:55:07,292 --> 00:55:09,954
- When are you gonna name the day?
- Raise your head.

663
00:55:10,128 --> 00:55:12,255
What's the next movie?
Give us the scoop.

664
00:55:12,430 --> 00:55:15,126
Right here. How many more
records are you gonna set?

665
00:55:15,300 --> 00:55:18,599
Right over here. Come on.
Give us a smile. It won't kill you.

666
00:55:18,770 --> 00:55:20,670
- Howard, this way.
- Beautiful.

667
00:55:20,839 --> 00:55:23,330
Over here, over here, Mr. Hughes.

668
00:55:23,508 --> 00:55:25,942
When are you gonna fly
around the world again?

669
00:55:26,111 --> 00:55:30,104
You gonna fly with Kate next time?
Did you get Ionely without her?

670
00:55:30,282 --> 00:55:34,343
- Talk to Lindbergh about your flight yet?
- Where's Linda Darnell tonight?

671
00:55:34,519 --> 00:55:37,818
- Please, Mr. Hughes.
- Right here. Right here, Mr. Hughes.

672
00:55:37,989 --> 00:55:40,480
Are you trying to be more famous
than Lindbergh?

673
00:55:41,193 --> 00:55:44,924
You know,
fame is supposed to be my turf.

674
00:55:47,165 --> 00:55:48,792
L.B.!

675
00:55:51,436 --> 00:55:54,803
If you don't get more distinguished
every time I see you.

676
00:55:54,973 --> 00:55:56,998
You look so beautiful.

677
00:56:04,783 --> 00:56:06,410
Is that true?

678
00:56:15,227 --> 00:56:17,092
Don't worry about it, Howard.

679
00:56:17,262 --> 00:56:20,925
She's just working the room.
It's her job, baby.

680
00:56:23,969 --> 00:56:27,769
<i>Sultry Southern tigress Ava Gardner
dazzles the room tonight.</i>

681
00:56:27,939 --> 00:56:30,169
<i>She's the newest star
in the MGM galaxy.</i>

682
00:56:30,342 --> 00:56:33,971
<i>And believe you me.
She puts the "cheese" in "cheesecake."</i>

683
00:56:36,214 --> 00:56:41,743
<i>Well, Jane Eyre has been selling popcorn
for over a hundred years, L.B.</i>

684
00:57:22,494 --> 00:57:23,927
Hello.

685
00:57:25,563 --> 00:57:27,121
Hello.

686
00:57:32,337 --> 00:57:35,204
Could you reach me a towel?

687
00:57:42,647 --> 00:57:44,376
I...

688
00:57:45,517 --> 00:57:48,748
I really can't do that.

689
00:57:50,388 --> 00:57:51,912
I'm sorry.

690
00:58:16,748 --> 00:58:21,082
I'm an idiot. I'm a complete idiot,
and I'm sorry.

691
00:58:21,419 --> 00:58:25,014
- Forget it.
- No, no. I'm a vain, preening ass...

692
00:58:25,190 --> 00:58:30,184
...without a single redeeming feature.
- That's not true. You have very good teeth.

693
00:58:30,695 --> 00:58:32,162
Come on.

694
00:58:33,031 --> 00:58:37,365
I've got a better idea. Take me flying.
Or better yet, I'll take you flying.

695
00:58:37,535 --> 00:58:39,264
Do your worst, Miss Hepburn.

696
00:58:48,380 --> 00:58:52,214
Don't be so squirmy. You're gonna
get on famously with Father and Mother.

697
00:58:52,384 --> 00:58:56,013
And I'm sure they'll like you too.
Once they get to know you.

698
00:59:04,329 --> 00:59:07,127
- Hello! Hello!
- Kath, hello.

699
00:59:07,298 --> 00:59:08,856
Kathy.

700
00:59:11,803 --> 00:59:15,534
- Who's that with the camera right there?
- That's my ex-husband, Ludlow.

701
00:59:15,707 --> 00:59:17,971
Father and Mother are just mad
about Luddie.

702
00:59:18,143 --> 00:59:22,477
- What the hell's he doing here?
